    "content": "Pruritus is a common manifestation of Hodgkin lymphoma, occurring in approximately 30% of patients, and can precede the diagnosis by up to 5 years. Patients with Hodgkin lymphoma may present with constitutional symptoms (B symptoms) including weight loss, fever, and night sweats, along with painless lymphadenopathy. Laboratory findings often include normocytic anemia, elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), and occasionally eosinophilia. Initial evaluation should include a complete blood count, comprehensive metabolic panel, and imaging studies such as CT scans of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis to assess the extent of disease. Diagnosis is confirmed by excisional lymph node biopsy demonstrating Reed-Sternberg cells in an appropriate cellular background."
