  "source": {
    "file_name": "The Lancet: Lupus Nephritis",
    "content": "Serological markers are essential in the evaluation of patients with suspected lupus nephritis. Anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) are positive in more than 95% of SLE patients, making a negative result useful for excluding the diagnosis. Anti-double-stranded DNA (anti-dsDNA) antibodies are more specific for SLE and have a strong association with lupus nephritis; rising titers often correlate with disease activity and may precede clinical flares. Complement levels (C3, C4) are typically reduced during active disease due to consumption in immune complex formation, and their normalization may indicate response to therapy. The combination of elevated anti-dsDNA antibodies and low complement levels has a high predictive value for active lupus nephritis. Other autoantibodies, such as anti-Smith (anti-Sm) and anti-ribonucleoprotein (anti-RNP), may also be present but are less specific for nephritis. While these serological tests are valuable for diagnosis and monitoring, kidney biopsy remains the gold standard for confirming lupus nephritis and determining its class according to the International Society of Nephrology/Renal Pathology Society (ISN/RPS) classification, which guides treatment decisions."
